{"type":"text","text":"{
  "id": "196bfafbdf68ce62",
  "subject": "Overview of Union Trust Bank’s Dispute Resolution Process",
  "from": "mcp.test.dki2@gmail.com",
  "date": "Sun, 11 May 2025 07:11:27 -0700",
  "snippet": "Dear Mark, Thank you for reaching out and for your continued interest in how Union Trust Bank manages customer complaints and disputes. Below is a concise overview of our current dispute-resolution",
  "body": "Dear Mark,\n\nThank you for reaching out and for your continued interest in how Union Trust Bank manages customer complaints and disputes. Below is a concise overview of our current dispute-resolution framework, followed by answers to the specific points you raised.\n\n1. How a dispute is initiated \n   •  Customers can lodge a dispute through any branch, our 24-hour contact centre, secure online banking, or by written request.  \n   •  On receipt, we acknowledge the complaint within five (5) business days and assign a dedicated case manager. A reference number is supplied so the customer can track progress online or by phone.\n\n2. Investigation & provisional credit (card-transaction disputes)  \n   •  The case manager gathers supporting documentation (transaction record, receipts, merchant correspondence, etc.) and, where relevant, contacts the merchant or the card network.  \n   •  In line with card-scheme rules, we issue provisional credit within ten (10) business days whenever an investigation is expected to exceed that timeframe.  \n   •  Evidence is assessed by both our Payments Operations team and an independent Compliance officer to ensure objectivity.\n\n3. Timeframes & key milestones  \n   •  Standard cases – target resolution within thirty (30) calendar days.  \n   •  Complex cases – may extend to sixty (60) days; if that occurs, the customer receives a written update explaining the reason and revised timeline.  \n   •  Resolution letter – once a decision is reached we provide a written summary of our findings, any adjustments made, and next-step options.\n\n4. Documentation we request  \n   •  Dispute/chargeback form (digital or paper)  \n   •  Copy of the account statement showing the transaction(s) in question  \n   •  Relevant receipts, invoices, e-mails or chat transcripts with the merchant  \n   •  Photo ID (for first-time complainants who have not previously verified via our digital channel)\n\n5. Escalation avenues  \n   •  Internal: customers may ask for a secondary review by our Dispute Resolution Committee (headed by a senior vice-president who was not involved in the original decision).  \n   •  External: if still unsatisfied, they can raise the matter with the Financial Services Ombudsman or the appropriate card-scheme arbitration panel. We supply full contact details in the resolution letter.\n\n6. Recent process updates  \n   •  Electronic signature acceptance and a secure upload portal launched Q4-2021 to streamline documentation.  \n   •  Pandemic-related merchant-response extensions reduced from 45 to 30 days as of 1 February 2022, bringing us back in line with pre-COVID timeframes.\n\n7. Aggregate performance (2021)  \n   •  12,437 disputes processed  \n   •  93% resolved within 30 days  \n   •  1.8% escalated beyond the bank  \n   •  Customer-satisfaction rating: 4.5 / 5\n\n8. Glamour Gadgets case (publicly disclosable details)  \n   •  Dispute received 7 January; provisional credit issued Day 14.  \n   •  Investigation concluded Day 28; merchant accepted liability; permanent credit posted Day 30.  \n   •  Customer notified at every milestone through the secure portal and by e-mail.\n\nI hope the above answers your questions. If you need further details or would like to arrange an interview, please let me know – I’m happy to provide additional materials, anonymised statistics, or walk you through a redacted case file.\n\nBest regards,\n\nJane Doe  \nSenior Manager, Customer Advocacy  \nUnion Trust Bank  \n☎ +1 (555) 987-6543  \n✉ jane.doe@uniontrustbank.com\n"
}","annotations":null}

